Review: If I told you this movie begins like an episode of Eastbound and Down you would not be prepared for the extent to which that is the case.
My favorite Jackass segment has always been Danger Ehren skipping down the street in a fairy outfit putting quarters in the expired meters before parking enforcement can write a ticket.

The main thing of this movie is seeing all your favorite Boston locations in their filthy 70’s glory. The acting is good. The script is better than the direction and cinematography. I always wonder when they film professional sports games for a movie, how do they do that? Is it scripted? Do they just play for fun? I hope so I love frivolity.

A lot different and better than I assumed based on seeing clips of the worst parts while flipping through daytime cable (the parts about the aliens being Weird). An emphasis on FUN! The first third rules. It’s visually interesting and playful and a celebration of 80’s kitsch which is often terrible but not here. Geena Davis is an all timer. I wish it had more musical numbers.

Watching the original film earlier in the day primed me to be all in from the first moments, and I was. I have been seeing a lot of movies this year that make me go "What are they doing are you allowed to do this??" and I cant tell exactly what they are trying to do or if it's good or bad but I love it. I felt that way again watching thisI loved the stuttering hiccup that repeated…

Movie: The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the Desert

Review: I would recommend this movie to anyone. I can’t remember who said this showed big Wes Anderson  influence after we saw it at the Egyptian, sorry, but I see it more every time I watch-from a technical/formal angle. From an emotional standpoint I’ve never seen Wes come close to the wallops this one packs.  reallly appreciated Rhys Darby this go
made it a half hour in, so bad it feels like it’s on purpose as a joke or?They make fun of dick jokes, while also just constantly doing dick jokes, for instance.I like Jason Schwartzman’s t shirt

This has such a vibrant fluid expressive dynamic style, visually a live action Into the Spiderverse. I've never looked to Wes Anderson for emotional engagement (though occasionally get some by surprise) but I get the feeling if you're on his wavelength and sharing all his particular interests and points of reference, you might feel something big. If nothing else this is an exhibition of technical mastery  Love it

EXCELLENT 4dx design. May be the best I’ve x-perienced. The movie itself wasnt quite to my tastes but I appreciate the sentiment on behalf of teens all over the world. The technical execution though….Carnage was so scary. If I were a child and I saw the scene when he first shows up I’d have had nightmares forever.
I see this movie every so often and it’s always better than I remember, and somehow different
